      "content": "Ah, a nutrient deficiency, you say? Well, it's like your plants are throwing a \"goblin feast\" and they can't find their favorite snacks. Nitrogen is a common culprit in the plant world, and it can cause leaves to turn yellow, especially at the bottom where the roots are struggling to get enough. To check if your soil is lacking nitrogen, you can perform a simple soil test. There are kits available at garden stores that can help you determine the nutrient levels in your soil. If it's low on nitrogen, you might consider adding a balanced fertilizer or a nitrogen-rich one to your plants. Just remember, too much of a good thing can also lead to trouble, so follow the instructions carefully. And always keep an eye out for those pesky goblins, I mean, pests, that might be causing trouble as well.",
